		<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 p-comment h-entry" id="comment-70395">
				<div id="div-comment-70395" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/796f8b42e7fea56c22dfc0a8cb26a08f?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='u-photo avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn">Richard Kirk</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2007/01/02/wikipedia-advertising/#comment-70395">
			2007-01-03 at 10:16</a>		</div>

		<div class='e-content p-name p-summary'><p>I support advertising on Wikipaedia.</p>
<p>I feel that modest advertising could be used without changing the nature of the Wikipaedia. There have been sensible suggestions to restrict the size and scope of advertising. There are sensible projects, such as the rescuing of orphaned copyright works that could use the funds to the general good. The comments supporting advertinsing seem modest and reasonable: the comments against are mostly a single line. </p>
<p>There are conditions. Clearly the whole Wikipaedia project has been supported by volunteers who would not be happy with their work going to make some accountant a millionaire. I am disturbed by the initial statements, gloating over &#8216;hundreds of millions of dollars&#8217;. We have seen what the Big Money Demon did for Googles &#8220;Do No Evil&#8221; motto. I would like to know more about what the money is for, and where it will go before we draw the pentacle&#8230;</p>
</div>
		<div class="reply">
					</div>
				</div>
		</li><!-- #comment-## -->
