		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2007/01/02/wikipedia-advertising/#comment-112898">
			2012-10-23 at 21:53</a>		</div>

		<div class='e-content p-name p-summary'><p>[...] well have destroyed the project; I advocate neither, though I have advocated huge revenues in the past) would be a billion dollar company by valuation and perhaps revenue as well &#8212; Wikimedia. I [...]</p>
</div>
		<div class="reply">
					</div>
				</div>
		</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 p-comment h-entry" id="comment-120212">
				<div id="div-comment-120212" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e8d99bd01104273eb5550c6c39770f5b?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='u-photo avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn">Marc Selman</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://gondwanaland.com/mlog/2007/01/02/wikipedia-advertising/#comment-120212">
			2013-12-06 at 5:18</a>		</div>

		<div class='e-content p-name p-summary'><p>I support ads on Wikipedia if the ads are related to the content of the article. It could actually be helpful in some cases. Maybe they could have a fixed location called &#8216;related advertisements&#8217; or something like that so the ads don&#8217;t mix with the article content.</p>
<p>If I was reading an article about some device I could see ads to buy one.<br />
If I was reading an article about a famous person I could see ads for posters, books merchandise etc about that person.</p>
</div>
		<div class="reply">
					</div>
				</div>
		</li><!-- #comment-## -->
